The interview - Blood returned safe 
Héma-Québec yesterday celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice, because Héma-Quebec has become a supplier of the safest blood and efficient in the world. 
And most importantly, he regained the confidence of the public who had been seriously shaken by the tainted blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s. 
As we know, national reserves managed by the blood transfusion service of the Canadian Red Cross have been infected by human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C during the 1980s. 
Faced with this tragedy and public discontent, the Government of Canada established in February 1994 a public inquiry, headed by Justice Horace Krever inquiry, which aimed to clarify the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and make recommendations for such a disaster never happens again. 
While the Krever delay in filing its report, while some provinces have set up a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada. 
In Quebec, the committee Gélineau has fulfilled that mandate. 
In the wake of reports Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve the Quebec and Canadian blood supply for all other provinces and two territories. 
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began operations, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary. 
The situation was discouraging. 
By dint of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and field work during the years that followed, we have regained the confidence of the public, "she says proudly affirm before the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Héma-Québec. 
Dr. Décary Keep in mind that "confidence is something extremely fragile." 
From its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle. 
At that time, there were in Europe at the outbreak of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, new variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, said that holding the fort since its founding in 1998. 
"And we did not know at all if the disease could be transmitted through blood. 
It was then supported on one of the main recommendations and reports Krever Gélineau that when we do not know that a serious illness and may result in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, instituting action exclusion. 
In April 1999, has refused the blood of people who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980. 
But a few years ago, it has been demonstrated beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood. 
This episode has shown that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense. " 
In 1999 appeared on the market a technique much more sensitive HIV testing: the nucleic acid testing (NAT) to detect directly in donated blood the virus itself rather than antibodies against the virus, which were based on tests used previously. 
The TAN helped to shorten the silent period, which runs between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in blood by our technical specialist explains. 
It was able to reduce that period to less than one week. 
It has thus been reduced substantially the risk that some donors are infected without knowing it and we can not detect them. 
These improvements have helped reduce the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion. 
Today, a person over 12 million at risk of receiving blood contaminated with HIV. 
"In other words, this means that it will distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV. 
As Héma-Quebec distributing each year between 400 000 and 500 000 blood products, it will take more than 24 years before that occurs a case of transmission of HIV through a blood product. 
I think we can now feel comfortable to receive or to prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health, "said the CEO of Héma-Québec. 
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products. 
You never know what disease will emerge in the system. 
As recently as last year appeared on the island of Reunion Chikungunya virus which, like the West Nile virus is transmitted by an insect in the blood. 
We must be constantly vigilant, "continues Dr. Décary before emphasize that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide a sufficient supply. 
"The needs are increasing as the population ages. 
The treatments being more aggressive, patients often need a refill in red blood cells or platelets. 
The aging population also has consequences on the network of blood donors which includes an average of only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate blood. " 
Any healthy person, aged 18 and over the eligibility criteria may yet give blood every 56 days, six times a year. 
On average, 14% of those offering their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled in a country where malaria is rife, they will be excluded for a period of one year. 
"With these 3%, we can maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals. 
The shortages are very rare. 
But we must renew members of the network of donors as they get older and can not donate their blood. 
It is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors. 
Life today is so rampant, there is rarely time to place an hour to give his blood "is sorry Francine Décary. 
With an annual budget of $ 297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, the eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burned. 
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which manages also the only bank cord blood in Quebec. 
The umbilical cord that was once regarded as biomedical waste is full of a rich blood stem cells can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia. 
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, the bank thousandth of our sample of cord blood and is expected to draw more miles per year. 
We should start to propose for transplants at the beginning of next year, "says Dr. Décary describing this program from cord blood as very popular. 
"Many mothers are disappointed not being able to access" because Héma-Québec can not afford to offer this program complex and expensive in all hospitals in Quebec. 
