Rescue Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans agree 
The Bush administration and leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 30s. 
The new version of the plan of 700 billion U.S. dollars to curb the financial crisis that rocked Wall Street for months has yet to be ratified by both houses of Congress. 
It provides a better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure repayment of public money committed, new provisions to limit the number of houses seized for non-payment and a right to look at the salaries paid to executives of companies rescued. 
U.S. Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, the chairman of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative to the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, following a marathon two-day negotiations. 
"We have made great progress toward an agreement that will be effective on the market," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson. 
"Everything has been done in order to shield the real economy and ordinary Americans of the current crisis on Wall Street," said the Democrat. 
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg. 
The negotiations had turned into a sprint in the final hours for fear of the effect that would cause another failure on the mood of investors. 
The deadline we had given was the opening of markets this morning. 
Associated late in the negotiations, the two presidential candidates were American rather support the agreement, without fail, however, to express their dissatisfaction that one is compelled to reach this end. 
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed the addition of certain provisions in the agreement, particularly to enable owners to keep their homes and on the wages of surviving leaders of enterprises by the state. 
"When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to congratulate. 
But these measures are necessary, "he commented on the airwaves of American television. 
Asked about another channel to vote for whether the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, responded: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so." 
"The outline that I read [show] that is something we will all have to digest and with which we can move forward. 
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable, "he said. 
The plan of 700 billion aims to buy with the money of taxpayers bad debts, assets at risk and unsaleable U.S. financial institutions. 
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble which first led to the collapse of risky mortgages (subprime) before spreading to other forms of more widespread credit titles (PCAA) and lead to a freeze of liquidity and the stampede of banks and financial institutions. 
This is a group of elected Republicans who had derail the first draft agreement last week. 
It is believed to have come out of this impasse since the Democrats have agreed that certain "toxic" companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased. 
To round off the corners for everyone to Congress, it has also added a provision stipulating that if the government had to take losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help recover his bet. 
The new plan provides for the payment of an initial tranche of 250 billion which could add another 100 billion if the President deems necessary. 
The other payment of 350 billion should be endorsed by another vote of Congress. 
In exchange for its support, Washington will get stakes in companies that rescued him earn dividends if profits and that it will sell when the storm has passed. 
The federal government will be able to delay proceedings seized on housing attached to loans under this plan and to set limits on compensation and severance packages paid to executives of companies affected. 
The architects of the plan would see it put to the vote in the House of Representatives today, and the Senate Wednesday. 
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light. 
Voices have indeed continued to rise yesterday against the project, both in the Republican camp as a Democrat. 
"Obviously, Washington does not hear you," said the address to his constituents the Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the Finance Committee of the House. 
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem. 
Yes, there are solutions. 
But not one that is to take advantage of taxpayers. " 
Convenor of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus skeptics," the Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but reaches the same conclusion. 
"Four hundred prominent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize, we have written to tell us: we ask the Congress not to hurry and scrutinize the way forward," he said yesterday. 
At the same time, Europe had once again demonstrated the global nature of the crisis. 
After an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries have announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis to 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion U.S.). 
The intervention of governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas has indicated that it would acquire its rival in full sinking since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion U.S.) in the crisis-risk mortgages in the United States. 
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is part of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers. 
"This is not money lost, said yesterday the Dutch Finance Minister, Wouter Bos. 
In return, we get the right to vote at the bank and influence. 
It's just something that investors and households appreciate now that uncertain times ahead. " 
