Hepatitis: where do we consult a doctor? 
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from hepatitis B or C chronic, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death. 
An estimated one hundred miles patients with hepatitis in Hungary, but only seven miles after treatment. This is because patients often do not know they are infected. 
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver caused by different viruses. 
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are typical, but pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other. 
Hepatitis viruses, according to the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (eg food or water contaminated), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretions, saliva). 
For travelers, it is anyway recommended to be vaccinated against the virus A and B. There is no vaccine against C. 
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor physical condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea. 
Then develops on the skin and white of the eye visible jaundice, stools become clearer and urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks. 
Throughout the world, each year a million people die from the most serious form of the disease, like cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B. 
The main reason is that according to estimates, only one patient in ten receives medical treatment. 
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer. 
Most patients do not know the virus reached because the pathogenic gene destroyed so insidious liver cells. In many cases the first symptoms appear after 20 to 30 years. 
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing. 
The contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: those who underwent blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattooed. 
Currently, there figure to 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis type C in the world. 
Since the disease can be detected by a routine examination in the laboratory, it is advisable to consult his doctor from the observation of symptoms of unknown origin. 
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented. 
On 30 September is the Day of hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world. 
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic cirrhosis of the liver caused by viruses, on the causes of development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease. 
